note_en:
Britons could be given a legal right to work from home to ensure that they are not forced to go back to workplaces  after the lockdown under plans being considered in Whitehall.
 Officials at the Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy department have raised the issue of enshrining a right to work from home in law as part of a suite of options to ease the lockdown, The Telegraph can reveal.
 One source said the idea of a legal right was suggested by officials during talks about the Government&#39;s return to work package.
 It would mean staff would not feel  compelled to go in to the office, while limiting the costs for employers who have to make their workplaces safe for social distancing.
 The idea – still in its infancy – has won the support of Government ministers who have drawn up the plans to encourage people to return to work and get the economy motoring. One said: &#34;It makes complete sense.&#34;
  The measure could prove popular in the so-called- red wall seats won by the Tories at December&#39;s election. Boris Johnson, the Prime Minister, committed his Government to making flexible working a  default right for workers in the party&#39;s 2019 manifesto.
 It said: &#34;We will encourage flexible working and consult on making it the default unless employers have good reasons not to.&#34;
 The idea of more protections to work from home were contained in a review of modern-day working by Matthew Taylor in 2017, which said: &#34;Encouraging flexible work is good for everyone and has been shown to have a positive impact on productivity, worker retention and quality of work.&#34;
 In the Government&#39;s response in 2018, ministers said that, &#34;as part of the statutory evaluation of the Right to Request Flexible Working in 2019, the Government should consider how further to promote genuine flexibility in the workplace&#34;.
 A source familiar with the thinking behind the plans said a legal right to work from home – or a commitment to one – would ensure that there are not huge queues at stations when commuters try to return to work once the lockdown eases.
 Transport authorities have warned the two-metre social distancing rules would mean trains and buses  would have to run 85 per cent empty to ensure travellers are kept apart.
 The Liberal Democrat frontbencher Layla Moran said any new law could be a &#34;win-win&#34; for employers and workers.
 &#34;By introducing this law, the Government will be giving the individuals even more control over their work-life balance, leading to improved mental health and more productivity,&#34; she said. &#34;It would also help address disparities in accessibility to the workplace, faced especially by those with childcare or other caring responsibilities.
 &#34;I believe this change would benefit both the employees and the employers, and has the potential to be a win-win.&#34;
 Frances O&#39;Grady, the TUC general secretary, told The Telegraph: &#34;The right to work from home would be a big step forward. People in all types of job need to be given more control over their hours and where they work. That&#39;s why we&#39;ve called for all workers to have a day one right to flexible working.&#34;
 A report from the TUC last week found that four in 10 workers are are concerned about not being able to socially distance from colleagues when back at work.
  The study also found more than a quarter were concerned about not being able to socially distance from customers or clients. One third were concerned about exposing others in their household to greater risk.
 The Unison union also reported that some of its members had said they were &#34;terrified that, if forced to go into work, they might take the virus home – with potentially devastating consequences&#34;.
 A Whitehall source told The Telegraph: &#34;We are engaging with key stakeholder and industry groups, as well as the unions, on safe working once lockdown measures have been relaxed.&#34;
 A Government spokesman said: &#34;The Business Secretary continues to work with businesses, union leaders and the science and medical community so we can ensure workplaces are safe for those who will go back to work once the measures are relaxed and give people the confidence to return to work.&#34;
 If ministers take the plans forward it would align the UK with Germany, which last week unveiled proposals to  introduce a legal right to work from home after the pandemic.
 Hubertus Heil, the Social Democrat labour minister, said employment legislation would be tabled in the autumn, making Germany and Finland the only countries in the world to have the right to home working enshrined in law.
 Mr Heil told Bild am Sonntag: &#34;Everyone who wants to and whose job allows it should be able to work in a home office. We are learning in the pandemic how much work can be done from home.&#34;
